.TH DETACH 1 "2021-07-04" "detach-process" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
detach \- spawn a new process and detach it from the current session
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B detach
.RI [OPTIONS] " -- " program " [ARGS...]"
.SH DESCRIPTION
The
.B detach
utility launches a program in a separate session so it continues running
independently of the interactive shell.
It forks, starts a new session, redirects standard input to
.IR /dev/null ,
and redirects standard output and standard error to temporary files in
.IR /tmp .
The
.RB \-\-
argument separates detach options from the command to run and is required
when options are used.
The parent process displays the child PID and the paths used for standard
output and standard error, then terminates.
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
.B \-\-help
Show this help message and exit.
.TP
.B \-\-pid FILE
Write the child process ID to
.IR FILE .
.TP
.B \-\-stdin FILE
Read the standard input from
.IR FILE
instead of
.IR /dev/null .
.TP
.B \-\-stdout FILE
Write the standard output to
.IR FILE
instead of a temporary file.
.TP
.B \-\-stderr FILE
Write the standard error to
.IR FILE
instead of a temporary file.
.TP
.B \-\-
End of options. Required when options are used.
.SH OUTPUT
On success, the parent process outputs:
.TP
.B PID:
The process ID of the detached child process.
.TP
.B stdout:
The file used to capture the child's standard output.
.TP
.B stderr:
The file used to capture the child's standard error output.
.TP
.B pid:
When
.B \-\-pid
is provided, the PID is also written to the specified file.
.SH EXIT STATUS
.TP
.B 0
Success.
.TP
.B > 0
An error was encountered.
.SH EXAMPLES
Start a ping command detached from the current session:
.PP
.RS
detach -- ping -c 10 google.com
.RE
.PP
Write the PID and the standard output and error to specific files:
.PP
.RS
detach --pid /tmp/ping.pid --stdout /tmp/ping.out --stderr /tmp/ping.err -- ping -c 10 google.com
.RE
.SH FILES
.TP
.I /tmp/stdout.XXXXXX
A temporary file for standard output generated by
.BR mkstemp (3)
when
.B \-\-stdout
is not provided.
.TP
.I /tmp/stderr.XXXXXX
A temporary file for standard error generated by
.BR mkstemp (3)
when
.B \-\-stderr
is not provided.
.SH SEE ALSO
.BR mkstemp (3),
.BR setsid (2),
.BR fork (2),
.BR execvp (3)
.SH AUTHOR
Vladislav Punko <iam.vlad.punko@gmail.com>
